"{\"uid\": \"thesouthafrican.com-sport-paris-olympics-2024-eurosport-ousts-bob-ballard-for-sexist-comment-at-paris-olympics\", \"text\": \"Copyright Blue Sky Publications (Pty) Ltd. All Rights Reserved.  thesouthafrican.com is a division of Blue Sky Publications Ltd. Reproduction without permission prohibited  Home\\u00bbSport\\u00bbParis Olympics 2024\\u00bbEurosport ousts Bob Ballard for sexist comment at Paris Olympics  Eurosport has removed commentator Bob Ballard from its team at the Paris 2024 Olympics following a sexist remark he made.  Eurosport has parted ways with commentator Bob Ballard following a sexist remark he made about Australia's female swimmers.  This decision came swiftly after the incident went viral on social media.  The controversy erupted during the women's 4x100m freestyle relay at the Paris 2024 Olympics, according toThe Gaurdian.  Australia's team, featuring Mollie O'Callaghan, Shayna Jack, Emma McKeon, and Meg Harris, clinched gold in a dramatic finish.  However, Ballard's comments overshadowed their victory.  As the team celebrated their gold medal, Ballard remarked, \\\"Well, the women just finishing up. You know what women are like \\u2026 hanging around, doing their makeup.\\\"  His sexist remark was met with outrage from many, including his co-commentator Lizzie Simmonds, who called the remark \\\"outrageous.\\\"  Simmonds, a former Olympic swimmer herself, did not hold back, according toDeadline.  She stated, \\\"It was completely inappropriate and disrespectful.  It's disappointing to see such comments at a time when we should be celebrating athletic achievement.\\\"  Eurosport was quick to respond.  In a statement, the broadcaster announced, \\\"During a segment of Eurosport's coverage last night, commentator Bob Ballard made an inappropriate comment.  To that end, he has been removed from our commentary roster with immediate effect.\\\"  Ballard has yet to address the comment publicly. His silence on the matter has only fuelled further criticism.  Social media users and sports fans have expressed their dismay, emphasising that such sexist remark have no place in modern sports broadcasting.  The Australian women's relay team had reason to celebrate beyond the gold medal.  With a time of 3 minutes 28.92 seconds, they secured their fourth consecutive gold in this event.  Emma McKeon also made history by winning her sixth gold medal, becoming Australia's most decorated Olympian, according toThe Independent.  Despite the negativity surrounding Ballard's sexist remark, the team's achievement was a testament to their hard work and dedication.  The focus now shifts back to their extraordinary performance, which has been overshadowed by the controversy.  Sporting events, especially the Olympics, are meant to be moments of unity and celebration. Ballard's comment detracted from the true spirit of the games.  It is crucial for commentators to uphold the respect and dignity of allathletes.  In the wake of this incident, Eurosport has reaffirmed its commitment to maintaining high standards of commentary and sportsmanship.  The broadcaster's swift action reflects a growing intolerance for sexist remarks in sports media.  As for the Australian swimmers, their triumph remains a highlight of the Paris Olympics. Their gold medal is a testament to their skill and teamwork.  In the end, the focus should remain on celebrating the athletes' success.  The Paris 2024 Games have already provided numerous moments of inspiration.  Let us keep the spotlight where it truly belongs - on the incredible performances and achievements of the athletes themselves.  Let us know by clicking on the comment tab below this article or by emailinginfo@thesouthafrican.comor sending a WhatsApp to 060 011 021 1.  You can also follow@TheSAnews on XandThe South African on Facebookfor the latest news.              WIN R2 000: Take The South African's SASSA Survey  The South African is hiring! Freelance writing positions available  Follow